522. The insertion which is found after this line in the Digby MS. (and in no other) consists of eight lines taken from the original text of the passage 545-580, which was rewritten by the author: see ll. 561*—566* and 579* f.

523ff. ‘Can a house be built without timber? But of what use is timber to the builder if it be not hewn ?’ ‘Nonne' for ‘Num,' as frequently: see note on v. 731. It seems that ‘sibi' refers to the builder rather than to the house; in any case, it has no reflexive sense. Finally‘ligna' is here used as a singular feminine: all the MSS. have ‘foret' inl. 524 and ‘valet ' in 525.

The idea of the passage seems to be that good laws are as the material, and the ruler as the builder of the house.
